{"candidates":[{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only in the mid-zone error regime where the majority is fragile: base candidate error e must satisfy 1/(k+1) < e < k/(k+1) so that some correct majorities are breakable, AND critic recall on wrong candidates must exceed the break-rate of correct majorities (recall_wrong > falseflag_rate_correct), with critic precision on wrong candidates > 0.5. Outside this zone harness ties or loses.\", \"mechanism\": \"Self-consistency relies on majority frequency. When e is very low (as in observed data), correct majorities are super-stable (4/5 or 5/5 right) and filtering can only break them via false flags → net harm or zero. When e is very high, majorities are already wrong and filtering cannot recover without a near-perfect critic. The strict-benefit zone is where majorities are 3/5 or 3/7 — correct but fragile — so a critic with recall_wrong > falseflag_rate_correct removes enough wrong answers to flip 3/5→2/3 (benefit) while false-flaging few enough correct answers to avoid 3/5→2/3 (harm). The net benefit is recall_wrong × P(fragile-correct) − falseflag_rate_correct × P(fragile-correct), which is positive only in the mid-zone.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"odd k ≥ 5\", \"candidate error e in (1/(k+1), k/(k+1))\", \"critic with recall_wrong > falseflag_rate_correct and precision_wrong > 0.5\"], \"excludes\": [\"e ≤ 1/(k+1) (stable correct majorities, observed easy-set regime)\", \"e ≥ k/(k+1) (stable wrong majorities)\", \"even k (tie-breaking complications)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=7, e≈0.33 (mid-zone), critic recall_wrong=0.6 and falseflag_rate_correct=0.1: harness accuracy is LOWER than or EQUAL to self-consistency despite recall > falseflag rate\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, e≤0.15 (low-zone, observed): harness accuracy strictly exceeds self-consistency\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=7, e≈0.33, a question-adaptive critic with identical recall_wrong and falseflag_rate_correct as a fixed critic yields different harness accuracy, contradicting the mechanism that only aggregate rates matter\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is the mechanistic base-case: a single fixed-precision critic operating in the mid-zone. It refutes the observed-data extrapolation (which lives in the low-error tail) by showing the strict-benefit zone is structurally inaccessible at e≤0.05. The decisive experiment sweeps k∈{5,7,9} across e∈{0.15,0.33,0.55} with a controlled critic (recall 0.6, falseflag 0.1), using 120 items × 5 seeds = 600 samples per cell, ~270k tokens total — fitting the 300k budget.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"},{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"},{"role":"mention","target":"2d711b2eb5fff4e61cba262914dc9aa29cf142c91d43bf4fffdda495e76c90c4"}],"typicality":0.85},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic is question-adaptive: it must concentrate recall on questions where the candidate majority is fragile (margin ≤ 1) and concentrate precision on questions where the majority is stable, yielding strict benefit over both fixed critics and self-consistency. A fixed-precision critic cannot strictly beat self-consistency in any regime.\", \"mechanism\": \"A fixed critic applies its recall and falseflag rate uniformly across all questions. On stable-majority questions, any nonzero falseflag rate breaks correct majorities with no compensating benefit (no wrong answers to catch). On fragile-majority questions, recall must be high enough to flip them. A fixed critic faces a binding tradeoff: raising recall to help fragile questions raises falseflag harm on stable ones. An adaptive critic decouples these: it can set near-zero falseflag on stable-majority questions (precision→1) while setting high recall on fragile-majority questions. The strict benefit is the adaptive-critic gain minus the fixed-critic gain, which is positive whenever the question distribution mixes stable and fragile majorities (which it always does at finite k). The causal mechanism is information-theoretic: the critic observes an additional signal (its own assessment) that is correlated with majority fragility, and conditioning on it strictly improves the filtering policy.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"any k ≥ 5\", \"any e in (0,1) where the question distribution includes both stable and fragile majorities\", \"critic with access to a fragility-correlated signal (e.g., its own confidence, candidate agreement pattern, or a separate probe)\"], \"excludes\": [\"fixed-precision/recall critics (by hypothesis they cannot strictly beat SC)\", \"uniform-error questions where all majorities have identical fragility\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"A fixed-precision critic with ANY recall/precision combination strictly beats self-consistency at k=7, e=0.33 — if so, the question-adaptivity claim is unnecessary and the candidate is refuted\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"An adaptive critic using a fragility signal achieves the SAME harness accuracy as a fixed critic with identical marginal recall and falseflag rates — if so, adaptivity provides no additional benefit and the mechanism is refuted\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The adaptive critic's fragility signal is shown to be uncorrelated with actual majority fragility (p > 0.05 on a held-out calibration set), yet harness still strictly beats SC — if so, the causal mechanism is wrong\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This candidate negates the fixed-critic abstraction directly, arguing that strict benefit requires question-adaptive critic behavior. The decisive experiment uses k=7, e≈0.33 (mid-zone from candidate 2d711b2e), with 3 critic arms: (1) fixed critic at recall=0.6/precision=0.5, (2) adaptive critic using candidate-agreement as fragility signal, (3) adaptive critic using critic-confidence as fragility signal. Each arm runs 120 items × 5 seeds = 600 samples, ~180k tokens, within budget. The key test is whether adaptive arms strictly beat both the fixed critic and SC while fixed critic does not beat SC.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"},{"role":"dependence","target":"5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"},{"role":"mention","target":"2d711b2eb5fff4e61cba262914dc9aa29cf142c91d43bf4fffdda495e76c90c4"}],"typicality":0.7},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"No critic-filtering architecture can strictly beat self-consistency when the candidate pool and critic share the same model family, because the critic's error pattern is positively correlated with the candidate pool's error pattern (shared blind spots), making falseflag_rate_correct ≥ recall_wrong on the questions that matter. Harness strictly beats SC only with an orthogonal critic (zero error-correlation with candidates) in the mid-zone error regime.\", \"mechanism\": \"Self-consistency fails when the majority is wrong. A critic can only help by catching wrong candidates that the majority missed. But if the critic shares the model family's blind spots (same training data, same reasoning patterns), it will fail to catch exactly those wrong candidates that the pool also got wrong (low recall_wrong on the relevant errors) while still having nonzero falseflag rate on correct candidates (which the pool got right but the critic may second-guess). This creates a structural inequality: recall_wrong < falseflag_rate_correct whenever the shared-error correlation is positive. The harness can only strictly beat SC when recall_wrong > falseflag_rate_correct, which requires the critic's errors to be uncorrelated with (or anti-correlated with) the candidate pool's errors — an orthogonal critic. The observed data (v4-pro critic on v4-pro candidates, v4-flash critic on v4-flash candidates) exhibits exactly this failure: same-family critics with positive error correlation, yielding net zero or net harm.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"any k ≥ 5\", \"mid-zone e in (1/(k+1), k/(k+1))\", \"critic from a DIFFERENT model family than candidates (orthogonal error pattern)\"], \"excludes\": [\"same-family critic (structurally cannot strictly beat SC)\", \"low-zone or high-zone error (ties or losses regardless of critic orthogonality)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"A same-family critic (e.g., v4-pro critic on v4-pro candidates) at k=7, e≈0.33 strictly beats self-consistency — if so, the orthogonality requirement is refuted\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"An orthogonal critic (e.g., Claude critic on Gemini candidates) at k=7, e≈0.33 does NOT strictly beat self-consistency despite recall_wrong > falseflag_rate_correct — if so, orthogonality is insufficient and the mechanism is incomplete\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Measured error correlation between same-family critic and candidate pool is ≤ 0 (non-positive), contradicting the shared-blind-spot assumption — if so, the causal story is wrong\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is the atypical candidate: it identifies a confound (shared model family) that may explain ALL observed null results, and predicts that the strict-benefit regime requires crossing model families. The decisive experiment has 4 cells: {same-family, cross-family} × {fixed critic, adaptive critic}, all at k=7, e≈0.33 (mid-zone). Each cell: 120 items × 5 seeds = 600 samples. Cross-family cells use Gemini-2.0-flash as critic on Gemini-2.5-pro candidates and vice versa. Token budget: 4 cells × ~65k tokens ≈ 260k, within 300k. The critical prediction is that ONLY the cross-family cells show strict benefit, while same-family cells tie or lose regardless of adaptivity.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"ba687c5f145e404c53a84549cf366e0b6e0106eec67404c07231357fed09e672"},{"role":"mention","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"}],"typicality":0.4}]}